From Late {{inh|en|enm|acūte||of a disease or fever: starting suddenly and lasting for a short time; of a humour: irritating, sharp}}, from {{der|en|la|acūta}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=acūte, adj.|id=MED434|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> from {{m|la|acūtus||sharp, sharpened}}, {{glossary|perfect}} {{glossary|passive}} {{glossary|participle}} of {{m|la|acuō||to make pointed, sharpen, whet}}, from {{m|la|acus||needle, pin}},<ref>{{R:Oxford Dictionaries Online}}</ref> from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂eḱ-||sharp}}. The word is cognate to {{doublet|lang=en|notext=1|ague||acute, intermittent fever}}.

As regards the noun, which is derived from the verb, compare {{cog|enm|acūte||severe but short-lived fever; of blood: corrosiveness, sharpness; musical note of high pitch}}.<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=acūte, n.|id=MED433|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>

